<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09117f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09117f">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09117f"> 117(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> marchstone</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Roman Law&rdquo;: By <i>fas</i> was understood the will of the gods, the laws given by heaven for men on earth, &hellip; embodying rules of conduct. &hellip; It punished &hellip; the displacement of a boundary or a landmark, not so much because the act was provocative of feud, as because the <mark>march-stone</mark> itself, as the guarantee of peaceful neighbourhood, was under the guardianship of the gods. <small> <cite a>&ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo;</cite></a> <a name="EBRL1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL1"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXIII p. 528</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
